The effects of wealth and other factors on obesity

Mai Phuong Pham Huynh, Judy Hao, Helen Hsu, Hayden Truong

4/29/2021

1. Load packages and prepare data set

To start with, we need to load the necessary packages and data sets. The data sets are obtained from The National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES)’s 2017-2018 data wave. We will use the demographics data (DEMO_J.xpt), dietary data (DR1TOT_J.xpt), and body measures data (BMX_J.xpt).

full1$BMXBMI[full1$BMXBMI %in% seq(0.0,18.4,0.1)] <- "Underweight"

full1$BMXBMI <- as.factor(full1$BMXBMI)

2. Study income distribution

Now, we study the income distribution.

hist(full$INDHHIN2, main = 'Figure 1. Distribution of Income', xlab = 'Income')

The histogram suggests us to factorize the income variable, INDHHIN2, into 4 levels: low income (0-5), middle lower income (6-10), middle upper income (11-15), and high income (>70).

full1$BMXBMI <- as.numeric(full1$BMXBMI)
full1$INDHHIN2[full1$INDHHIN2 %in% c(1,2,3,4,5)] <- "Low Income"
full1$INDHHIN2[full1$INDHHIN2 %in% c(6,7,8,9,10)] <- "Lower Middle Income"
full1$INDHHIN2[full1$INDHHIN2 %in% c(11,12,13,14,15)] <- "Higher Middle Income"
full1$INDHHIN2[full1$INDHHIN2 %in% c(77,99)] <- "High Income"
full1$INDHHIN2 <- as.factor(full1$INDHHIN2)

First, let us see which income group contributes the most to the total population and which contributes the least.

full1 %>%
  mutate(INDHHIN2 = fct_infreq(INDHHIN2)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(INDHHIN2)) + geom_bar() +
  labs(title = 'Population in Each Income group', 
       x = 'Income group')

Then, we study the relationship between income and BMI.

ggplot(full1, aes(INDHHIN2,BMXBMI)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = 'Figure 2. Income vs. BMI', x = 'Income', y = 'BMI')

The boxplot does not give us much information about the relationship between income and obesity level (measured by BMI index). However, we also recognized that the low income and lower middle income groups have respondents with highest BMI index.

To have a more concrete information about the proportion of each weight level in an income group, we create a proportional table to calculate the percentage of underweight, normal, overweight, and obese people in each income group. From this table, we are able to create a bar plot to see how the proportions vary from among income groups.

table1 <- table(full1$BMXBMI,full1$INDHHIN2)

ggplot(table2, aes(x=Var2, y =Freq, fill=BMI)) + 
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  labs(title = 'Figure 3. Proportion of each weight level in each income group', 
       x = 'Income group', y = 'Proportion (%)') + 
  scale_fill_discrete(name="BMI",
                         breaks=c("1", "2", "3", "4"),
                         labels=c("Normal", "Obese", "Overweight", "Underweight"))

From the proportional table and the barplot, we observe that for each weight level, the ascending order of the proportion of that weight level in each income group is as followed.

  • Underweight (BMI < 18.5): Higher Middle < Lower Middle < High < Low

  • Normal (18.5 \(\leq\) BMI < 25): High < Lower Middle < Low < Higher Middle

  • Overweight (25 \(\leq\) BMI < 30): Lower Middle < Low < Higher Middle < High

  • Obese ( BMI \(\ge\) 30): Higher Middle < Low < High < Lower Middle

We observe that the proportion of overweight is the highest in the High Income group, which does not fit our initial expectation that rich people tend to be more healthy as they would have more financial resource to better their health. However, since the data we have for people in this income group consists of only 174 observations, which is 10 times less than other income groups. Hence, it may not be evident enough to conclude that people in the High Income group are more likely to be overweight compared to other income groups.

However, the proportion of obesity are the highest in the Lower Middle income group and third highest in the Low Income group after the High Income group. This trend fits our initial hypothesis that poorer people are prone to be more obese, which can be a result of their constant usage of cheap fast food and lack of financial resources for sports and gymnastic activities.

3. The impact of marital status and education level on obesity level

In the previous section, we found that people from Low Income and Lower Middle Income are more likely to be obese compared to people from other groups. Now, we will look more closely into the impact of marital status and education level on the obesity level for each income group.

a) Group 1. Low Income

We first look at the Low Income group (income index is no more than 5).

# low income
low_inc <- full %>%
  filter(INDHHIN2 <= 5, DMDMARTL != 77, DMDEDUC2 != 7, DMDEDUC2 != 9)

The average BMI for low-income group is 29.71 and the median BMI is 28.7.

For this group, we do not observe the correlation between BMI and marital status. However, we remark that married people have the biggest range on BMI and that people living with partners have the smallest range on BMI.

Similarly, we do not see a correlation between BMI and education level. The only thing we can tell from the graph for education is that people with an education degree at college or above seem to have the smallest range, which is from 18 to 42. This phenomenon might imply that educated people are more conscious of their health. However, we are not able to draw a conclusion from the plot we generated.

For the Lower Middle Income group, we still do not see a correlation between BMI and marital status. However, we notice that each marital status group with lower middle income shows a wider range of BMI than those with lower income. This phenomenon might be caused by the fact that the lower-middle-income group can afford more options for food and nutrition than the lower-income group. Or it can be simply caused by the difference in sample size.

On the other hand, we still do not find a correlation between BMI and education level. Similar to what we observed for marital status, we find that each marital status group with lower middle income shows a wider range than those with lower income. The reason again might be that the Lower Middle Income group is financially capable to afford more options for nutritious food. Or it can simply due to the difference in sample size.

For the High Income group, we discovered a slightly negative correlation between BMI and marital status. The plot illustrates that married people on average have a higher BMI than single people do. This finding matches our assumption that single people tend to take care of their health and thus are less likely to suffer from obesity.

On the other hand, we observed a slightly positive correlation between BMI and education level in the high-income group. This finding does not match our hypothesis, in which more educated people are less likely to be obese. The reason for this deviation might be that rich and educated people who care about their health may have excessive nutritious intakes, which would result in a higher average BMI.

4. Number of kids/elders in the household

In this section, we want to investigate the relationship between family structure and its corresponding obesity level. Our motivation is that families with more care-needed members (children and elders) are more likely to have lower rate of obesity. The rationale is that families with more children and elders tend to be more attentive to their diets. Based on the previous analysis, we expect that people from the High Income, Lower Middle Income, and Low Income groups will have the lowest number of family members that need special care as they have relatively high rate of overweight and obesity.

We first sum the variables DMDHHSZA (number of children 5 years or younger), DMDHHSZB (number of children 6-17 years old), and DMDHHSZE (number of adults 60 years or older) to represent the total number of people who need special care in the respondent’s household. Then, we calculate the average number of people with special care for each income group. This number is found to be highest for the Lower Middle Income group (1.555) and lowest for the Low Income group (1.280).

low_inc1 <- low_inc %>%
  select(DMDHHSZA, DMDHHSZB, DMDHHSZE) %>% 
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(total= DMDHHSZA + DMDHHSZB + DMDHHSZE)
tot_lowinc = mean(low_inc1$total)
tot_lowinc
## [1] 1.280355
low_mid_inc1 <- low_mid_inc %>%
  select(DMDHHSZA, DMDHHSZB, DMDHHSZE) %>% 
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(total= DMDHHSZA + DMDHHSZB + DMDHHSZE)
tot_lowmidinc = mean(low_mid_inc1$total)
tot_lowmidinc
## [1] 1.555431
high_mid_inc1 <- high_mid_inc %>%
  select(DMDHHSZA, DMDHHSZB, DMDHHSZE) %>% 
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(total= DMDHHSZA + DMDHHSZB + DMDHHSZE)
tot_highmidinc = mean(high_mid_inc1$total)
tot_highmidinc
## [1] 1.458
rich1 <- rich %>%
  select(DMDHHSZA, DMDHHSZB, DMDHHSZE) %>% 
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(total= DMDHHSZA + DMDHHSZB + DMDHHSZE)
tot_rich = mean(rich1$total)
tot_rich
## [1] 1.50289

The numbers found above does not meet our initial expectations. Hence, for future improvement, we want to look more closely into the inter-connection among income, family structure, and obesity level (measured by BMI index) by adding more indepedent variables into the model.
